  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Organisation for Public Health Interventions and Development (OPHID) leads the FACE-Pediatric HIV program, which aims, &quot;to eliminate new HIV infections in children and improve survival of mothers and children in line with the National Strategic Plan (2011-2015). The program&#x2019;s objectives are to 1) provide technical and other assistance to national PMTCT programwithin the Ministry of Health and Child Care;2)strengthen provision of clinical services for comprehensive PMTCT; 3)strengthen pediatric HIV services;4)conduct operational research to inform evidence-based policies and program strategies; 5)strengthen continuum of care for mother, infant and family. The program is national in coverage and its activities target health care workers at all levels, community leaders, volunteers, pregnant and lactating women (HIV+/HIV-), their male partners, children and families. As a local organization in partnership with the MOHCC, OPHID&#x2019;s program prioritizes strategies to cascade and reinforce the national elimination agenda with stakeholders at all levels (national, provincial, district and community). The program is in continuous engagement with MOHCC to ensure sustainable systems are established.  A rigorous approach to M&amp;E has been adopted with activities to strengthen national M&amp;E activities (i.e site supervision), robust data collection, high standard of data quality assurance systems (onsite data verification), enhanced data analysis as well as the systematic dissemination and review of results (routine data review meetings) supporting evidence-based planning and implementation. Changes in pipeline funding has influenced the coverage and scope of the program.</narrative>
  </description>
